'''Kisshōten''' ({{lang|ja|[[Wiktionary:吉祥天|吉祥天]]}}, lit. "Auspicious Heavens"), also known as '''Kichijōten''', '''Kisshoutennyo''' (吉祥天女), or '''Kudokuten''' (功徳天), is a Japanese female {{ill|Deva (Buddhism)|en|Deva (Buddhism)|qid=Q4089509|lt=deity|1=Deva (Buddhism)}}, adapted via {{ill|Buddhism in Japan|en|Buddhism in Japan|qid=Q736311|lt=Buddhism|1=Buddhism in Japan}} from the {{ill|Hinduism|en|Hinduism|qid=Q9089|lt=Hindu|1=Hinduism}} goddess {{ill|Lakshmi|en|Lakshmi|qid=Q131443|lt=Lakshmi|1=Lakshmi}}. Kisshoutennyo is sometimes named as one of the [[:en:Seven Gods of Fortune|Seven Gods of Fortune]] (''fukujin''), replacing either [[Jurōjin]] or [[Fukurokuju]].<ref name=BritishMuseum>{{cite web|title=Wooden figure of Kichijōten|url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/highlights/highlight_objects/asia/w/wooden_figure_of_kichij%C5%8Dten.aspx|publisher=The British Museum|access-date=27 August 2012}}</ref>  For example, in the 1783 edition of the [[Butsuzōzui|Butsuzōzui compendium]] (reprinted in 1796), Kichijōten replaces [[Fukurokuju]] as one of the seven fukujin.<ref name="Butsuzōzui077">{{cite web|title=Butsuzōzui (Illustrated Compendium of Buddhist Images)|url=http://www.lib.ehime-u.ac.jp/SUZUKA/316/index.html|location=Ehime University Library|page=(077.jpg)|language=ja|format=digital photos|date=1796|access-date=14 May 2016|archive-date=10 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181010061804/http://www.lib.ehime-u.ac.jp/SUZUKA/316/index.html|url-status=dead}}</ref>  She is considered to be the goddess of happiness, fertility, and beauty.<ref name=BritishMuseum/><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-02-10 |title=Kichijoten Japanese Lucky Go11ess of Beauty |url=https://mythologysource.com/kichijotenl-japanese-goddess/ |access-date=2023-03-01 |archive-date=10 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230210030230/https://mythologysource.com/kichijotenl-japanese-goddess/ |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Kisshōten (Kichijōten)|url=http://www.philamuseum.org/collections/permanent/305645.html|publisher=Philadelphia Museum of Art|access-date=27 August 2012}}</ref>  Kisshoutennyo's iconography is distinguished by the [[Cintamani#Nomenclature.2C orthography and etymology|Nyoihōju gem (如意宝珠)]] in her hand,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Neighbour-Parent |first1=Mary |title=Kichijouten 吉祥天 |url=http://www.aisf.or.jp/~jaanus/deta/k/kichijouten.htm |website=JAANUS |publisher=Atsumi International Scholarship Foundation}}</ref> Kisshōten and the Nyoihōju gem are both represented by the symbol of the ''{{ill|Kagome crest|en|Kagome crest|qid=Q16851345|lt=kagome|1=Kagome crest}}''.

When Kisshoutennyo is counted among the seven fukujin<ref name="Butsuzōzui077" /> and fellow Fukujin [[Daikokuten#Go11ess Daikokutennyo|Daikoku]] is regarded in feminine form,<ref name="Butsuzōzui059">{{cite web|title=Butsuzōzui (Illustrated Compendium of Buddhist Images)|url=http://www.lib.ehime-u.ac.jp/SUZUKA/316/index.html|location=Ehime University Library|page=(059.jpg)|language=ja|format=digital photos|date=1796|access-date=14 May 2016|archive-date=10 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181010061804/http://www.lib.ehime-u.ac.jp/SUZUKA/316/index.html|url-status=dead}}</ref> all three of the Hindu {{ill|Tridevi|en|Tridevi|qid=Q1137755|lt=Tridevi|1=Tridevi}} goddesses are represented in the Fukujin, with Daikoku representing {{ill|Parvati|en|Parvati|qid=Q170485|lt=Parvati|1=Parvati}} and [[Benzaiten]] representing [[Saraswati]].

